25|$|In 1899 {{the state}} {{legislature}} passed a new constitution, with requirements for poll taxes and literacy tests for voter registration which disfranchised most <b>black</b> <b>Americans</b> in the state. Exclusion from voting had wide effects: it meant that <b>black</b> <b>Americans</b> could not serve on juries or in any local office. After a decade of white supremacy, many people forgot that North Carolina had ever had thriving middle-class <b>black</b> <b>Americans.</b> Black citizens had no political voice in the state until after the federal Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 were passed to enforce their constitutional rights. It was not until 1992 that another African American was elected as a US Representative from North Carolina.|$|E
